Share link


Share on GooglePlus
Share on LinkedIn
Tumblr
Whatsapp
Add to Black Book




 

															by Christian Barker


April 29, 2014 11:37 AM






“Marketing is very important,” says the chairman of Tom Ford International, Domenico De Sole. “In luxury, you have to have an aesthetic, a vision for the brand. However, in the end, the product is everything.” (Photo by Tom Ford)








Exclusive Q&A: The boss of Tom Ford International discusses entrepreneurship, persistence, product quality, pragmatic creativity and the importance of thinking big.







Christian Barker: Together, you restored the fortunes of Gucci and built the company into one of the world’s pre-eminent fashion groups, and now you’ve established a multi-billion-dollar business in Tom Ford International. Suffice it to say, your partnership with Mr Ford is one of the most distinguished and successful in luxury. What is it about your personality and skillset that complements his personality and skillset?
Domenico De Sole: We’ve known each other for a long time. We’re very different, but we have the same vision about what a brand ought to be and what the vision of the brand should be — we’re very disciplined in understanding, especially the new company. We launched Tom Ford and everybody wanted to buy the products — but we wanted to keep it very exclusive. It’s a very complex universe. But we share the same vision and the same desire. I’m not a creative person, so I don’t design. One thing that helps me: Tom is a big persona in design and fashion, creativity. Everybody thinks of Tom as a creative director. The reality is he’s a very astute and rational person, and a very good businessperson. It’s very easy to have common ground with Tom, because he really understands. He understands business. If you’re creative, but not commercially aware, and nobody wants to buy your product, it’s useless.
The Tom Ford brand began with partnerships in eyewear, in fragrances. What was the strategy there?
 It was the type of products that Tom liked. Yes, it was a good financial base for the company. The key issue though, was that Tom liked them. You can’t force the designer to design products that he or she has no feeling for. It’s important to stay in an area that Tom would be comfortable in, that he really likes.
The quality level of all your products is stratospheric. I’m wearing one of your Private Blend fragrances, Azure Lime, which I put on at 8.30am and that will still be lingering when I get home at 8.30pm. Your garments and accessories, equally, are superbly constructed. It’s admirable, when so many fashion brands are all ‘smoke and mirrors’ — a veneer of luxury and glamour masking ordinary products.
 There are some businesses where marketing is very important. In luxury, you have to have an aesthetic, a vision for the brand. However, in the end, the product is everything. Of course, the stores must be consistent and all that — but if you peel that back, it’s the product. You can spend billions in marketing, but if the product is not consistent with the marketing, you won’t sell. You have to be clear about what the priority is. Tom has a great vision for the brand.
The Tom Ford suit is not only beautifully made, but incredibly distinctive in its shape, fit and details — a perfect melding of quality and aesthetics.
 Every great brand has to represent something. There are a lot of brands that make suits. But if we do suits like everyone else, there is no raison d’être. What Tom did [in creating the brand’s signature suit silhouette] was very exciting — it’s fashionable and it’s exciting. Even I wear it. I think you have to have a distinct look and distinct point of view. Otherwise nobody needed another brand to make nice suits.
One of the genius things about a Tom Ford suit is that its distinctive look pretty much functions as branding without a visible logo — I look at the lapels, the proportions, the nipped waist, the heroic shoulders and I know it’s a Tom Ford suit. Do you think that’s something that’s going to work in Asia, where more blatant branding seems to prevail?
 I think the Asian market has become a lot more sophisticated in the last few years. The brand is gaining much more traction. Menswear has always been strong in Asia. And we also have a very strong accessories market. In this market, accessories are the driver. I’m very bullish about Southeast Asia. With Gucci it was a very good business. Once you put together a good brand and a strong local customer base, it’s unbeatable.
Mr Ford recently stated his intention to grow the company into one of the five major luxury brands in the world. As chairman, the person responsible for overseeing that expansion, does that breadth of ambition daunt you, or does it excite you?
 At Gucci, a long time ago, a private equity firm owned the brand. It was not public yet. And I said [to the head of the equity firm]: “We’re going to be bigger than Chanel.” He said: “You’re crazy.” At the end of the day, you must have a great dream and great vision, or else you’ll never succeed.
Just a decade after founding the Tom Ford brand, you’re now doing roughly a billion dollars in sales annually. What advice would you give the founder of a start-up who aspired to generating similar revenue within 10 years of launching their business?
 My view is very simple — and that’s to stick it out. [In the early 1990s, before De Sole was appointed president, and Ford creative director] Gucci had been run into the ground. By the time we went public [in 1995], it was a really massive success. I recall my daughter asking me how we turned things around and I said: “Winners never quit.” I thought Gucci would be a great company. Even though it was broke, I always felt that if I stuck it out, the brand could be resurrected. And here we are now.
www.tomford.com


12


