Domenico De Sole, Gucci's Savior



  The last of the family managers had also allowed the company to sell such vulgarities as plastic and canvas luggage with the Gucci name, and Gucci goods were then paled on sale not just in Gucci stores but in plebeian department stores.  De Sole took over in 1993.  He had previously decided to abandon the somewhat unpredictable business climate of Italy to build a legal career in American.  He first helped Maurizio Gucci with a problem in 1984, and at that time Gucci lured De Sole from his law firm in Washington, D.C. to be the leader of Gucci's American subsidiary through a tax investigation by the Internal Revenue Service, which he did successfully.  Investcorp, which also owns other luxury companies such as Ebel, a Swiss watchmaker, and Chaumet, a French jeweller, took over Gucci from the family in September 1993, and at that time De Sole was summoned back to Italy to take charge of the entire company ("The velvet revolution" 70).De Sole was faced with two immediate tasks when he took over stewardship of the company.  First, he had to continue with the much-needed housekeeping which Investcorp had already started by such actions as cutting product lines; improving quality (no more plastic); closing unprofitable outlets; overhauling  stock-control and ordering-systems; and selling a palatial office in Milan in order to move Gucci's headquarters back to Florence.  Second, he had the more difficult task of making the Gucci name desirable in the marketplace once more.  In this regard, he decided that the company should become a  modern fashion house rather than continuing to concentrate on "classics" such as loafer shoes decorated with a horse's bit (first made in 1962) or handbags with bent bamboo handles (produced since 1947).  De Sole then handed over creative control to Tom Ford, an American designer, and the latter's use of vivid satin and deep velvet was the success ... 






